        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2017-12-04 04:35:03.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n(1 comment)\n\nI think the cleanups are fine, but it isn't clear if this patch addresses the primary complaint of LU-7058, which is that migrating a directory between MDTs (with '-m' option) fails if there is a trailing '/' after the directory name.  This patch looks like it is affecting OST object migration when a directory is specified on the command line?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "068cf007702a9d6b602ef63a4dfd016e27aec246",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 676,
        "name": "Steve Guminski",
        "email": "stephenx.guminski@intel.com",
        "username": "sguminsx",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2017-12-07 12:13:59.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n(1 comment)\n\nThe original problem reported in LU-7058 no longer seems to happen in master.  Directories are successfully migrated when the -m option is used with directory names that end with a slash.\n\nThis patch addresses the secondary problem you identified while investigating the ticket.  Despite the documentation claiming that directories can be migrated, -EISDIR is always returned when a directory argument is provided.  This patch recursively migrates the directory contents.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
